intent_divergence: intent.md is absent, so no divergence can be assessed.

`crates/ctx-cage/tests/` is the integration test suite for ctx-cage's sandboxing broker, proxy, wire protocol, bwrap argv construction, and CLI mode resolution — depending on it gets you nothing (it's a leaf test crate), but editing any public surface in `ctx_cage::{broker, bwrap, proxy, protocol, cli, summarize}` requires checking the matching file here.

Tests are split strictly by transport reality: `broker_loopback.rs` and one test in `proxy.rs` use real `UnixListener`/`UnixStream` pairs (with per-test unique socket paths via a shared pid+atomic-counter pattern to dodge parallel-test collisions), while `protocol.rs` uses pure in-memory `Vec<u8>` buffers and `bwrap_build.rs`/`cli.rs`/`summarize.rs` test pure functions with no I/O at all. `bwrap_build.rs` is the most load-bearing file for cross-cutting changes: it pins the exact three-token argv layout (`flag host cage`) that `common/`'s predicates and its own `assert_bind` helper both assume, plus the `CAGE_BIN`/`CAGE_RULES_PATH`/`CAGE_RUN_DIR` constants imported directly from `ctx_cage::bwrap` — renaming any of these breaks both this file and `common/mod.rs` in lockstep. `common/` supplies the only shared fixtures (synthetic `BwrapConfig`/`ClaudeBinds` plus argv predicates) used across the bwrap-related tests; everything else in this directory is self-contained per file with its own local fixtures (e.g. `proxy.rs`'s `cfg()`/`FakeUpstream`, `broker_loopback.rs`'s `drive`/`spawn_broker_thread`).

A shared discipline holds across all files: tests avoid real subprocesses and real sockets where possible (FakeSpawner in broker tests, UnixStream::pair in proxy tests, byte buffers in protocol tests), and any test touching the real filesystem uses a unique per-process/counter path to stay parallel-safe (`unique_socket` in broker_loopback.rs, the tempdir path in `cli.rs`'s `task_file_is_read_from_disk`, `bwrap_discover.rs`'s per-test tempdirs).